{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522949"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13860"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13860"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.35,0.01,0.05,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91351"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2400"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of fever, dry cough, and progressive shortness of breath. He has a medical history of acute myeloid leukemia, for which he completed a second round of chemotherapy (Cytarabine) two weeks ago, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. He has received several courses of antibiotics in the past month for recurrent fevers. His medications include prophylactic famciclovir, pegfilgrastim subcutaneously, metformin 1000 mg twice daily, and pantoprazole 40 mg daily. He works as a gardener and recently spread mulch in several gardens. He has not had any recent sick contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 38.4\u00b0C, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, pulse rate 112/min, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 92% on room air. Auscultation of the chest reveals diffuse crackles bilaterally. A chest radiograph shows diffuse reticulonodular opacities in both lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial pneumonia","Cytarabine-induced pneumonitis","Pulmonary embolism","Viral pneumonia","Fungal pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly concerning for \u003Cstrong\u003Efungal pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E. He has multiple risk factors for opportunistic fungal infections, including neutropenia secondary to recent chemotherapy for acute myeloid leukemia and diabetes. His work as a gardener and recent exposure to mulch also raises the possibility of inhalation of fungal spores. The subacute onset of fever, cough, and dyspnea, along with diffuse reticulonodular infiltrates on chest radiography, is consistent with fungal pneumonia in this clinical context. The fact that this patient is already on viral prophylaxis, has received multiple courses of antibiotics without improvement, and is not currently on prophylactic trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole further increases his risk for fungal infections. Common causative organisms include \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. Fungal pneumonia occurs in up to 15% of patients with haematological malignancies and is associated with mortality rates of 30-80% despite treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the diffuse and nodular pattern on imaging, as bacterial pneumonia typically presents with more focal consolidation. Additionally, this patient has already received several courses of antibiotics without improvement, suggesting a non-bacterial etiology. Atypical bacterial pneumonia, such as that caused by \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia\u003C/em\u003E, or viruses, can present with diffuse infiltrates. However, the nodular pattern and immunocompromised status point more towards a fungal aetiology in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytarabine-induced pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication of chemotherapy that can occur within 1-3 weeks of treatment. While the timing would fit, the presence of fever and the patient\u0027s occupational exposure make an infectious cause more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with sudden onset dyspnea, pleuritic chest pain, and possibly hemoptysis. While patients with malignancy are at increased risk for thromboembolism, the presence of fever, diffuse crackles on examination, and reticulonodular infiltrates on chest radiography are inconsistent with pulmonary embolism. Additionally, the gradual onset over one week and lack of risk factors such as immobility make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is much less likely in this case, given the lack of any sick contacts, the degree of immunocompromise, and the nodular pattern on imaging which is more characteristic of fungal infection. The fact that the patient is already on famciclovir prophylaxis also argues against a viral aetiology (although it is not very effective against most respiratory viruses).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fungal pneumonia should be considered in immunocompromised patients presenting with respiratory symptoms and diffuse pulmonary infiltrates on imaging.","Risk factors for fungal pneumonia include neutropaenia, organ transplantation, chronic corticosteroid use, and HIV/AIDS.","Recent exposure to mulch or soil in immunocompromised patients increases risk of invasive fungal infections."],"references":["Connolly J JE, McAdams HP, Erasmus JJ, Rosado-de-Christenson ML. Opportunistic fungal pneumonia. J Thorac Imaging. 1999;14(1):51. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9894953/","Godoy MCB, Ferreira Dalla Pria HR, Truong MT, Shroff GS, Marom EM. Invasive Fungal Pneumonia in Immunocompromised Patients. Radiol Clin North Am. 2022 May;60(3):497\u2013506. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35534133/","Fort\u00fan J. Diagnostic and therapeutic approach to fungal pneumonia in the critically ill patient. Rev Esp Quimioter. 2022 Apr 22;35(Suppl1):97\u2013103. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35488836/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13860"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91351"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T15:24:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T15:25:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6477"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty